      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become interconnected in such a way that the state of one particle directly affects the state of the other, no matter the distance between them. It's like a pair of magical dice that always land on the same number, even if they're miles apart. Unlike classical correlation, where two objects might be connected through past interactions or shared experiences, entanglement happens instantaneously and independently of space and time. This means if you know the state of one particle in an entangled pair, you instantly know the state of the other, regardless of how far apart they are. It's a truly unique and non-intuitive aspect of quantum mechanics.",
