    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. i think i remember my prof mentioning something about it being 'spooky' though? like what is the actual difference in how the information is behaving compared to something classical? like if i have two gloves and i send one to the moon, that's correlation, right? why is entanglement \"spooky\" then?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your professor was likely referring to Albert Einstein, Boris Podolsky, and Nathan Rosen's famous 1935 paper, where they called quantum entanglement \"spooky action at a distance\". The \"spookiness\" comes from the fact that entanglement defies classical intuition and our traditional understanding of how information should behave. In classical scenarios, like sending a glove to the moon, information (or the glove itself) travels at a finite speed (the speed of light). However, with entanglement, the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance, without any apparent information transfer. This instantaneous connection doesn't follow the classical rules of cause and effect or the speed limit set by the speed of light, which is why it feels so \"spooky\" and counterintuitive. It's like having a pair of gloves that can instantly tell you if the other glove found a matching pair of socks, without you needing to receive any new information. This aspect of quantum mechanics challenges our classical notions of reality and locality.",
      "source": "target",
